'''Al-Malakut''' meaning ''Realm of Dominion'' ({{lang-ar|عالم الملكوت}}), is a realm of invisible, in [[Islamic cosmology]], containing several metaphysical beings and places in Islamic lore, like [[angels]], [[Shaitan|demons]], [[jinn]], [[Jahannam|hell]] and the [[Jannah|seven heavens]].<ref>Jess Hollenback ''Mysticism: Experience, Response, and Empowerment'' Penn State Press 1996 {{ISBN|978-0-271-04444-6}} page 259</ref> It is sometimes used interchangeable with ''Alam al Mithal'', but otherwise distinguished from it, as a realm above ''Alam al Mithal'', but still sublunary to [[Alam al Jabarut]], as a lower plane for angels, but still higher than the plane of jinn.<ref>Amira El-Zein ''Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn'' Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-815-65070-6}} page 49</ref> The higher realms are not separated worlds in Islamic thought, rather they impinges the realms below.<ref>Amira El-Zein ''Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn'' Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-815-65070-6}} page 6</ref>
==Imaginal Realm== The realm called ''Al Malakut'' or ''Alam al Mithal'' (translated as ''imaginal realm'') terms the concept of a realm where all ideas, thoughts and actions are manifested, including supernatural experiences,<ref>Hamid Naseem Rafiabadi ''Saints and Saviours of Islam'' Sarup & Sons 2005 {{ISBN|978-8-176-25555-4}} page 170</ref> conversations with angels and encounters with jinn.<ref>Jess Hollenback ''Mysticism: Experience, Response, and Empowerment'' Penn State Press 1996 {{ISBN|978-0-271-04444-6}} page 259</ref> Additionally, the lower soul ([[nafs]]), came from there and the dreamer enters this realm again during sleep.<ref>Duncan Black Macdonald ''Development of Muslim Theology, Jurisprudence, and Constitutional Theory'' The Lawbook Exchange 2009 {{ISBN|978-1-584-77858-5}} page 234</ref> It is held to be between the material realm ([[Alam al Mulk]]) and the spiritual realm (Alam al Jabarut).<ref>Victor Danner ''Kitāb Al-Ḥikam'' Brill Archive 1984 {{ISBN|978-9-004-07168-1}} page 71</ref>
